Here is an example of a JavaScript function that uses regular expressions to extract a three character code like "1Jn" from a filename in the format "57-1Jn.usfm":
```
function getCode(filename) {
  const regex = /^(\d+)-([A-Za-z0-9]{3})\.usfm$/;
  const match = filename.match(regex);
  if (match) {
    return match[2];
  } else {
    throw new Error("Invalid filename format");
  }
}
```
This function uses a regular expression to extract the three character code from the filename. The regular expression `/^(\d+)-([A-Za-z0-9]{3})\.usfm$/` matches any string that starts with one or more digits, followed by a hyphen, followed by exactly three characters that are either uppercase or lowercase letters or digits, and ends with the ".usfm" extension.

The `match` method is used to apply the regular expression to the filename, and if there is a match, it returns an array of matches. The second element of this array contains the three character code that we are looking for.

If there is no match, the function throws an error indicating that the filename format is invalid.

You can test this function by calling it with a filename in the format "57-1Jn.usfm" and it should return the three character code "1Jn".
